      passage: `<div style="text-align:center;font-weight:600;font-size:12px;margin:2px 0">Productivity Loss (Australian Dollars) Measured at Two Points After Each Program Began</div><table style="border-collapse:collapse;margin:6px auto"><tr><th style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px">Type of training</th><th style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px">12 weeks</th><th style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px">12 months</th></tr><tr><td style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px;text-align:center">EET</td><td style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px;text-align:center">268</td><td style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px;text-align:center">171</td></tr><tr><td style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px;text-align:center">EHP</td><td style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px;text-align:center">282</td><td style="border:1px solid var(--border);padding:3px 12px;text-align:center">436</td></tr></table>Michelle Pereira and colleagues proposed that bringing health improvements into workplaces would lift productivity by curbing absenteeism (ailing employees staying off work) and presenteeism (ailing workers laboring less efficiently). The team placed groups of Australian workers into two programs&mdash;one offering exercise training (EET), the other health-promotion seminars (EHP)&mdash;and then worked out each group&rsquo;s productivity loss at 12 weeks and at 12 months after the programs started (drawing on the 28 days before each point). Exercise training, they concluded, held productivity loss in check better than the seminars did, though the effect took a while to show.`,
